\begin_layout Subsection
Happiness and environmental quality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We present new evidence at national level that certain types of green and
 blue spaces near the home are linked to retrospective evaluations indicating
 higher life satisfaction, greater emotional wellbeing, and lesser negative
 affect.
 This evidence is not exceptionally robust, but for life satisfaction it
 is the first available on this question, and has significant potential
 for elaboration in future research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We show much stronger evidence on the related point that people are happy
 when they are 
\emph on
in
\emph default
 green and blue spaces.
 The effects we describe are both substantial and highly robust.
 This constitutes a new line of evidence in EQ and wellbeing research, and
 has significant implications beyond academic work.
\end_layout

